<h1>COMPANY HISTORY</h1>
<img src="img.jpeg"width="300"></img>
<p>The Daily Grind Coffee Shop is one of the most noticiable coffee shope in SOUTHAFRICA. One notable version of The Daily Grind Coffee shop was founded in 1995 in SouthAfrica, capetown,it is based in santon mall and began franchising nationally in 2000. It had locations across multiple provinces in SOUTHAFRICA and was recognized in Entrepreneur Magazine's Franchise 500 rankings in 2007.
Another version of The Daily Grind Coffee shop was founded in 2007 by NTANDO who were passionate about coffee. His goal was to create a shop that served the best cup of coffee in town while supporting fair trade and donating 5% of profits to farming communities. Over the years, this business expanded into a local coffee chain with many locations, each featuring a retro industrial vibe and educational signage about coffee.
Other locations are ROSEBANK,PORT ELIZABETH(boardwalk mall). This business specializes in freshly roasted coffee beans and loose-leaf teas and offers a 100% satisfaction guarantee for online purchases.</p>
<h2>MEET THE FOUNDER</h2>
<img src="img9.jpeg"width="200">
<p>NTANDO is the CEO of The Daily Coffee SHOP, a South African coffee franchise. He opened the first Daily Coffee Café in 2013 and expanded it into a franchise business in 2015. His background includes experience in hospitality, operations, finance, retail, marketing, interior design, and corporate governance.</P>
<h3>MISSION STATEMENT</h2>
<p><b>OUR MISSION IS :</b>"To bring back the warm, cozy coffee shop experience we all love, paired with delicious coffee that feels just like home. Every cup is served with care, and every customer is treated like family."
Another version of The Daily Grind Coffee Shop emphasizes traditional brewing methods combined with modern innovation, aiming to educate customers about coffee cultivation, roasting, and preparation while serving drinks that exceed expectations.</P>
<h3>COFFEE SOURCING AND SUSTAINABILITY PRACTICES</h3>
<img src="img1.jpeg"width="200"> <img src="img2.jpeg"width="200"></img>
<p>Coffee is one of the most popular beverages in the world, enjoyed by millions of people every day. But have you ever stopped to consider where your coffee comes from and how it is sourced? The sustainability and ethical sourcing of coffee is becoming an increasingly important issue in today’s society.
Sustainable coffee sourcing involves practices that aim to minimize the negative impact on the environment and promote the well-being of coffee farmers and their communities. This includes using methods that conserve water, reduce chemical use, and protect biodiversity. By supporting sustainable coffee sourcing, we can help protect ecosystems that are home to diverse species of plants and animals.
Ethical sourcing of coffee means ensuring that the farmers who grow and harvest the coffee beans are paid fair and just wages, are provided with safe working conditions, have access to medical services, and have access to education for their families. This is crucial for combating poverty and promoting social justice in coffee-growing regions. When we choose to purchase coffee that is ethically sourced, we can contribute to the improvement of the livelihoods of these farmers and their families.
Understanding the impact of sustainable coffee sourcing is important because it allows us to make conscious choices that align with our values. By opting for sustainably and ethically sourced coffee, we can support systems that promote environmental stewardship and social responsibility. So the next time you sip your morning cup of joe, take a moment to appreciate the efforts of those who work hard to bring it to your table while safeguarding our planet and its people.</p>
<h4> HOW WE COLLECT OUR RECIPE</h4>
<ol>
<li>Traditional Recipes – Many coffee recipes originate from cultural traditions, passed down through generations in coffee-producing regions.</li>
<li>Barista Innovations – Professional baristas experiment with different brewing techniques, ingredients, and ratios to create new recipes.</li>
<li>Scientific Research – Some recipes are developed through studies on coffee extraction, grind size, and brewing temperature to optimize flavor.</li>
<li>Community Contributions – Coffee enthusiasts share their favorite recipes online, in books, and through social media.</li>
<li>Industry Standards – Coffee companies and cafes refine recipes based on customer preferences and market trends.</li>



